<div id="review_3296270251" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3296270251" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3296270251?book_show_action=true">May 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible">audible</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=adventure">adventure</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=long">long</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=france">france</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=love">love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=victorian">victorian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hf">hf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2020-read">2020-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3296270251" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9579994567275962053"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28407.Germinal' title='Germinal by Émile Zola' rel='nofollow noopener'>Germinal</a> by <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4750._mile_Zola' title='Émile Zola' rel='nofollow noopener'>Émile Zola</a> takes place in a fictional mining town near the Belgium border of northern France. It lies in the vicinity of Marchiennes, a French commune in the Département du Nord. The story is about the haves and the have-nots, the bourgeoise mine owners, their managers and the hardscrabble poor working the mines. Along comes a young, idealistic youth of twenty one, Etiénne Lantier. He envisions what can be achieved if workers rise up and demand fair pay and better working conditions.</span>
  <span id="freeText9579994567275962053" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28407.Germinal" title="Germinal by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Germinal</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4750._mile_Zola" title="Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Émile Zola</a> takes place in a fictional mining town near the Belgium border of northern France. It lies in the vicinity of Marchiennes, a French commune in the Département du Nord. The story is about the haves and the have-nots, the bourgeoise mine owners, their managers and the hardscrabble poor working the mines. Along comes a young, idealistic youth of twenty one, Etiénne Lantier. He envisions what can be achieved if workers rise up and demand fair pay and better working conditions. They need to strike! How do the elderly, the middle aged and the young see this? We watch what unfolds over a year, from March 1866 through April 1867.<br /><br />Zola describes the landscape, the town and its people with finesse. The town, Montsou, is situated on a bleak windblown plateau. Flimsy, shabbily constructed workers’ abodes are lined up neat and prim in numbered areas. Conceived as model housing, they are in reality, shoddy and of substandard quality. The contrast between the wealthy and the poor comes to the fore. A sharp contrast is drawn also between the beauty of nature and its harshness; we see golden fields of crops shining in the sun, pelting rain, gloomy mists and the grime and rigors involved in the process of pulling the coal from the dark and dangerous mine pits where the young and the old work for little pay. How people behave living in such circumstances is a question asked. <br /><br />Zola plays with words. Look again at the name of the town, Montsou—mountain of coins. Do you catch what is said?<br /><br />Not only the physical landscape but also the characters are drawn with detail, with nuance. There are many characters, more than twenty. Etiénne is an outsider who comes to the town, but it is how the townspeople, individually and as a group, react towards him and interact with him that is central to the plot. Few authors are capable of drawing successfully such a large cast of characters. Successively, one learns the backstory of each. Given a group of them together, you grasp instinctively the vibes between them. It is through all of the characters together that the story is drawn, and it is through all of them together that Zola relays the message he is seeking to convey. <br /><br />The novel depicts extreme poverty and oppression, and yet at its end Zola succeeds in conveying the message that there is hope to be found in the future. Why? Because a seed has been sown. Stop and look at the book’s title-- <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28407.Germinal" title="Germinal by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Germinal</a>. This was the name given to the first month of the spring quarter of the French Republican calendar, which in 1793, after the French Revolution, replaced the Georgian calendar. The month and thus the book’s title is based on the Latin word germen, meaning germination. <br /><br />People do learn, family experiences pass from generation to generation. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Although the strike that occurred here did fail <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, in the future <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[more strikes will occur and <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, conditions for the poor and working class will be alleviated. It is through the author’s lyrical writing that this message is conveyed. <br /><br />The book was written between April 1884 and January 1885. On March 21, 1884, the right to strike was legalized in France.<br /><br />There are sections that are exciting, but it is not these sections that make the book special for me. For me, there are details in these sections that go overboard, for example the <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[sexual arousal between Etiénne and Catherine, when they are trapped, exhausted and starving, in the collapsed mine, is not believable. Neither was it necessary to have Chaval’s dead body drift up to them in the flooded mine <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Josh Dylan narrates the audiobook very well. He dramatizes, but for the most part not excessively. There is a bit too much at the end when the <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[mine has collapsed and workers are trapped <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. The speed and pacing is fine. Once you know how the character names are pronounced, they are not difficult to distinguish. This is important since there are so many. <br /><br />Roger Pearson has both translated and written the introduction to the book. In the audio format, the introduction is placed at the end. This is good since it reveals plot information which you do not want to read before having read the book! On the whole, I find it overly analytical. In my view, it is important to read a book, see how you react and judge for yourself what you think. With a good book, explanations are not necessary. The background information provided in the introduction is interesting.<br /><br />I very much like the descriptiveness of the writing. I marvel at the author’s ability to draw so many characters well, making it simple to quickly recognize who is being spoken of. I cannot say I related to any one of them closely, but as a group they seem realistic to me. Through them the book’s message is well conveyed. There is an honesty about human nature in Zola’s writing. This honesty appeals to me. This is my favorite book by the author, so far. Having read this, I now want to read more by Zola.<br /><br />***********************<br /><br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28407.Germinal" title="Germinal by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Germinal</a> 4 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/110871.Th_r_se_Raquin" title="Thérèse Raquin by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Thérèse Raquin</a> 4 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/371456.Nana" title="Nana by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Nana</a> 1 star<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28409.The_Masterpiece" title="The Masterpiece by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">The Masterpiece</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38819295.The_Bright_Side_of_Life__Les_Rougon_Macquart___12_" title="The Bright Side of Life (Les Rougon-Macquart, #12) by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">The Bright Side of Life</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/92967.L_Assommoir" title="L'Assommoir by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">L'Assommoir</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40128495.The_Beast_in_Man" title="The Beast in Man by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">The Beast in Man</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28413.The_Ladies__Paradise" title="The Ladies' Paradise by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">The Ladies' Paradise</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3888856.The_Kill" title="The Kill by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">The Kill</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18552501.Money__Les_Rougon_Macquart__18_" title="Money (Les Rougon-Macquart #18) by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Money</a> TBR</span>
