    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3273251790" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3273251790" />
    <a title="Jenna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3536004-jenna"><img alt="Jenna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535136437p2/3536004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3273251790?book_show_action=true">Apr 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenna" href="/user/show/3536004-jenna">Jenna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=classic-of-the-month">classic-of-the-month</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=out-of-europe">out-of-europe</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3273251790" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12015106284948053726"><b>&quot;In the old man’s time the miner lived in the mine like a brute, like a machine for extracting coal, always under the earth, with ears and eyes stopped to outward events. So the rich, who governed, found it easy to sell him and buy him, and to devour his flesh; he did not even know what was going on.&quot;</b><br/><br/><i>Germinal</i> is a book I&apos;ve been intending to read for a long time. I&apos;m not sure now was the best time because it&apos;s rather depressing, but it is also a good book and well worth reading.<br/><br/>Emile Zola wrote </span>
  <span id="freeText12015106284948053726" style="display:none"><b>"In the old man’s time the miner lived in the mine like a brute, like a machine for extracting coal, always under the earth, with ears and eyes stopped to outward events. So the rich, who governed, found it easy to sell him and buy him, and to devour his flesh; he did not even know what was going on."</b><br /><br /><i>Germinal</i> is a book I've been intending to read for a long time. I'm not sure now was the best time because it's rather depressing, but it is also a good book and well worth reading.<br /><br />Emile Zola wrote for the unheard masses, those suffering and powerless people whom the rich exploited. To those without voices he gave a voice. <br /><br />In <i>Germinal</i>, Zola tells the story of workers at coal mines in France. The suffering he describes as they spend their lives toiling away deep in the bowels of the earth is harrowing. The rich owners pay them barely enough to survive on and so they are always hungry. Children too are sent to work in the mines in order to supplement their family's meager income. The mines are dangerous places and many are injured, leaving the family to support a person who is unable to contribute. Of course, this was not just the case in France, but in many other countries as well. <br /><br />Because these poor people have little to no access to education, and because they have little time or energy to think, they have scant hope of changing their situation.  Etienne Lantier was a man who lost his job on the railway and because he was somewhat educated, he saw what the miners could not and gave them hope that together they had power. He organized a strike that had devastating consequences but which also gave hope to the hopeless. <br /><br />Zola paints a vivid portrait of this time and place and these miners and I was immersed in their lives, at times hoping with them, at times feeling their despair. I couldn't help comparing the rich owners to the corporations of today that are always striving to chip away at workers' rights. If allowed, most would have unsafe working conditions for their employees, work them longer and longer hours with less pay, and have little to no recourse for any suffering or injury they might sustain. Unfortunately, workers rights are being eroded, at least here in the US, and people have little or no time to think, and no hope that they have a voice or power to change things for the better. And then there is the developing world where rich corporations exploit the poor, basically using them as slave labor and granting them as few rights as workers had in Zola's time. Would Zola be shocked if he was alive today? Perhaps, perhaps not, but he no doubt would have striven to give the people a voice. <br /><br />My one complaint about this book is its sexism. The most glaring example is how when 15 year old Catherine is raped, Zola explains that her no didn't mean no and girls only said no when they really meant yes. Right after she is assaulted and her virginity stolen from her, we are told Catherine and her rapist get up and go about their way, "they stopped twice beside the canal, three times along the pit-bank, very cheerful now and occupied with little tender games."  Yes, you read that right! Catherine is brutally raped but, because she really did "want it" in spite of pleading with Chaval to stop, she jumps right up and goes skipping down the lane with her rapist, cuddling and happily playing little games. What the hell, Zola??? I was infuriated with that. <br /><br />Poor young Catherine then pairs up with Chaval, thinking she deserves no better than a man who raped her (oh wait, it wasn't <i>really</i> rape!) and who beats her on a regular basis. In some ways, her situation echoes that of all the miners and so perhaps Zola was using this symbolically. I get that, but not how Zola used the disgusting stereotype that a woman never really means no. A woman's "yes" means "yes" but her "no" also means "yes". Zola spoke for the worker's rights but not for women's rights. Yes, he was a product of his time, but it was still infuriating.<br /><br />That bitch aside, and it's a big bitch, I still am glad to have read this book. There are some tedious parts as there often are in classics. However, it is brilliantly written and though at times depressing, Zola reminds us there is always hope. Once the seed of thought has been planted and begins to germinate, people can find their own voices and power and, by working together, change things for the better. <br /><br /><i>April 2020 classic-of-the-month</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="12015106284948053726" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


