  <span id="freeText677636493650650503" style="display:none">I wonder, just how much suffering can the laboring masses endure? Further, why were revolutionary forces, acting to remedy that suffering, so successfully vilified, some even to this day? These thoughts arose while reading M. Zola’s excellent <i>Germinal</i>, a tale that grants a potent voice to the destitute unfortunates, in this case oppressed coal miners in northern France, amid the unrelenting contest with faceless capital.<br /><br />Recently, I listened to an old favorite, Hazel Dickens singing <i>Coal Miner’s Grave</i>.<br /><br /><i>Up there on that hillside, there's, an old miner's grave<br />And the briars and bushes, that a-bout, cover it up these days<br />And there's no one to claim it, or care if he's gone a-way<br />For he was only a miner, and it's only, a coal miner's grave.</i><br /><br />Oh, what miseries! Why did it take so long for us to assert our humanity? Have we even?</span>
