        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer151841438" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14481081773566364782">The wobbly cages descending into the pit, miners half-naked toiling in the scorching darkness of the mine’s galleries, the veins bursting and flooding the passages, the meager wages the miners receive at the end of the day, the wives desperately scouring for gruel each meal, the parents giving their daughters to the grocer to get flour and sugar; all recounted in a calmly detached voice. <br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1409441282i/10979537._SY540_.jpg' width='170' height='200' alt='Courrières Mine Disaster' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>Courrières Mine Disaster<br/><br/>Etienne, a vagrant worker, joined the fraternity and dissatisfied with the inhuman da</span>
  <span id="freeText14481081773566364782" style="display:none">The wobbly cages descending into the pit, miners half-naked toiling in the scorching darkness of the mine’s galleries, the veins bursting and flooding the passages, the meager wages the miners receive at the end of the day, the wives desperately scouring for gruel each meal, the parents giving their daughters to the grocer to get flour and sugar; all recounted in a calmly detached voice. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1409441282i/10979537._SY540_.jpg" width="170" height="200" alt="Courrières Mine Disaster" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Courrières Mine Disaster<br><br>Etienne, a vagrant worker, joined the fraternity and dissatisfied with the inhuman daily drudges and ambitious to rise above these defeated and resigned miners organized them into a union and led the strike. But the strike revealed as much the indifference of the owners and managers as the ignorance and violence of the miners. After many lives perished, many families shattered, many mines destroyed, the strike failed, the miners returned to work and Etienne left. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1409440697i/10979482._SY540_.jpg" width="170" height="200" alt="Emile Zola" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Emile Zola<br><br>In Germinal, Zola harmonized the detached narrative voice with the miner’s sub-human existence and their potential for gratuitous evil to evoke a chilling sonata that would haunt the reader long after the novel’s conclusion. </span>
