<div id="review_2108868187" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2108868187" />
    <a title="Tara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70459127-tara"><img alt="Tara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592666421p2/70459127.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2108868187?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tara" href="/user/show/70459127-tara">Tara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70459127-tara?shelf=1001-list">1001-list</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2108868187" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10329308986183695699"><i>Germinal</i> thoroughly described the social and political climate of a coal miners’ uprising in northern France in the 1860s. The book was admittedly slow to start, but once it finally got going, it was truly engrossing…up until the last 80 pages or so, when it anticlimactically trickled off to a fairly lackluster ending. Also, I could have done without the “dramatic” love triangle, which didn’t really add much to the book in my opinion.<br/><br/>At its best, however, the book was damned exciting. The unbear</span>
  <span id="freeText10329308986183695699" style="display:none"><i>Germinal</i> thoroughly described the social and political climate of a coal miners’ uprising in northern France in the 1860s. The book was admittedly slow to start, but once it finally got going, it was truly engrossing…up until the last 80 pages or so, when it anticlimactically trickled off to a fairly lackluster ending. Also, I could have done without the “dramatic” love triangle, which didn’t really add much to the book in my opinion.<br /><br />At its best, however, the book was damned exciting. The unbearably tense atmosphere of repressed rage Zola cultivated, and the explosive way in which he unleashed it, was nothing short of masterful. He had me so worked up at one point that I was eager to hurl bricks too, and my heart shouted and jeered in sympathetic ferocity along with my fellow strikers. That said, I must admit that I was listening to Arch Enemy at the time, and their music tends to make me angry and throw-y anyway. After all, death metal isn’t really noted for its <i>calming</i> effects.<br /><br />One thing’s for certain: after reading this book, I know I’ll never look at a Hot Dog on a Stick eatery in quite the same way. I won’t be able to read the phrase “stick it to the man” in as innocent a fashion as before either :O</span>
  <a data-text-id="10329308986183695699" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


